<methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Methods</title>
<para>Study Sites</para>
<para>Sampling took place in mid-September: the late dry to early wet season in South Africa.  Two study sites (A and B) were identified in Punda Maria in northern Kruger National Park, South Africa. This part of the Kruger National Park is characteristically dominated by C. mopane shrubveld, which typically occurs on basalt soils and is the largest and most homogeneous landscape in the park.  Sites A and B were located along a gradient, with Site A at the bottom of a slope and B at the top of the slope.  Site A was characteristically dominated by Colophospermum mopane and Euclea divinorum, while Site B consisted of a mixture of tree species, with the most abundant species being Afzelia quanzensis and Terminalia sericea.</para>
<para>Study species</para>
<para>Tree species were selected based on their major leaf phenological types. E. divinorum is an evergreen species and A. quanzensis, T. sericea, and C. mopane are deciduous.  A. quanzensis characteristically flushes green towards the end of the dry season before the start of the rains, and T. sericea characteristically contains little to no leaves for a large part of the lowveld winter (Sappi Tree Spotting 2007).  C. mopane shows variation in its timing of leaf drop, but tends to hold on to its leaves for as long as possible during the dry season (Dekker and Smit 1996).</para>
<para>Data Acquisition:</para>
<para>Tree Demographics</para>
<para>Tree height and stem diameter was recorded in individuals of each of the four tree species. The percentage leaf canopy on each tree was estimated based on the leaf abundance on the tree branches, and GPS locations were recorded for each tree.</para>
<para>Fluorometry: Photosynthetic Capacity of leaves</para>
<para>A fluorometer was used to estimate the photosynthetic capacity of each tree.</para>
<para>Root estimates</para>
<para>Five soil samples were collected below each tree canopy using a soil auger at a depth of 10cm, as well as a single soil sample at a depth of 50cm.  This was done to separate shallower horizontal roots from deeper vertical roots within the substrate.  Soil was classified into broad types using the hand test (Brown 2002). A proportion of each soil sample was sifted to find any roots, and these were classified as coarse live roots, coarse dead roots, fine live roots, or fine dead roots.  Coarse roots were determined to be thicker than the fine roots, and live roots were determined if the root could be bent without breaking and was moist in the centre.</para>
<para>Water Potential</para>
<para>A Scholander pressure device was used to determine water potential of the trees.</para>
</section>
</description>
</methodStep>
